  "body": "I am running geth locally on two different amd64 ubuntu 20.04 server machines with the [official docker image](https://hub.docker.com/layers/ethereum/client-go/v1.9.20/images/sha256-c78326a2ef4b37e05e75949b07fb655d5afde48d90a803abb9b6bb64379c823b?context=explore) and noticed that since the upgrade to 1.9.20, ssh sessions to this host machine regularly freeze. Sometimes for a minute, sometimes forever and I have to kill the ssh session. A ssh session also freezes if I have a second ssh session open in parallel works just fine.\r\n\r\nNo CPU spikes out of the usual, no RAM or disk/IO spikes neither, nothing out of the usual in the logs neither\r\n\r\nIf I stop geth, the freezes are gone and SSH works just like normal. `1.9.19`, which I ran for the full two weeks the release was out until I switched to `1.9.20` didn't show this behavior, nor any version before. I am fairly certain some change from 1.9.19 to 1.9.20 caused this.\r\n\r\n#### System information\r\n\r\nGeth version: `1.9.20`\r\nOS & Version: Ubuntu 20.04 LTS Server\r\nCommit hash : (if `develop`)\r\n\r\n#### Expected behaviour\r\nSSH sessions work and are not affected by geth\r\n\r\n#### Actual behaviour\r\nSSH sessions regularly freeze evidently caused by geth\r\n\r\n#### Steps to reproduce the behaviour\r\nRun geth for some hours on above described system.",
